objects.name: wishful woodchuck
objects.description: Wishful Woodchuck is a non-persistent Windows keylogger attributed to Turla by observed characteristics. It hooks the keyboard using Windows API calls (SetWindowsHookExW) and logs keystrokes to an encoded file (msimm.dat) in UTF-16, using a static multi-byte rotating XOR key embedded in the binary. It has no network communications or persistence capability. Multiple variants exist (x86/x64 DLLs and executables) and reuse indicators such as a hardcoded 100-byte XOR key, XOR 0x55 obfuscation of function and module names, and a TVer versioning string. The malware employs defense evasion via dynamic import resolution with XOR-obfuscated names, multi-byte XOR string/logfile obfuscation, and masquerading through filenames similar to legitimate Windows binaries (e.g., lmm32.dll vs imm32.dll).

objects.name: Turla
objects.description: The report states that the TVer string and XOR 0x55 encoding of Windows API function names are techniques previously observed in Turla binaries, suggesting Wishful Woodchuck was written by Turla. Turla’s relevant TTPs in this context include versioning via TVer strings, obfuscation of API names using XOR 0x55, and use of masquerading filename conventions.

objects.name: MITRE ATT&CK
objects.description: The report is compiled with respect to the MITRE ATT&CK framework, using its tactics, techniques, and identifiers to classify Wishful Woodchuck’s behaviors.

objects.name: Input Capture: Keylogging
objects.description: Wishful Woodchuck uses Windows API calls to log keystrokes.

objects.name: Obfuscated Files or Information
objects.description: Wishful Woodchuck uses multi-byte XOR obfuscation of strings in its binary and log file.

objects.name: Obfuscated Files or Information
objects.description: Wishful Woodchuck dynamically resolves Windows API functions using names XORed with 0x55.

objects.name: Masquerading: Match Legitimate Name or Location
objects.description: Wishful Woodchuck uses a filename (lmm32.dll) similar to a legitimate Windows signed binary (imm32.dll).

objects.name: wishfulwoodchuck_hardcoded_xorkey
objects.description: YARA rule to detect related activity.
objects.pattern:
rule wishfulwoodchuck_hardcoded_xorkey
{
    meta:
        author = "NCSC"
        description = "Finds binaries containing the hardcoded XOR key
from the keylogger binaries"

    strings:
        $xorkey = {0A 19 59 2D 6C 59 6F FA 8B 6F 9B FF 37 9B BD 7B 59 4B
7B DD 0F 64 91 C7 D6 9C 6F 7B 9C 01 9C 91 79 C7 C8 C9 DF E1 FA FF 04 08
59 E6 64 6D 37 9B 38 81 2D 81 65 7D 66 9A}

    condition:

uint16(0) == 0x5A4D and
uint32(uint32(0x3c)) == 0x00004550 and
all of them

}

objects.description: YARA rule to detect related activity.
objects.pattern:
rule wishfulwoodchuck_file_description
{
    meta:
        author = "NCSC"
        description = "Unique file description"

strings:

$description = "Multi-User Windows IMM32 API CIient DLL" wide

condition:

uint16(0) == 0x5A4D and
uint32(uint32(0x3c)) == 0x00004550 and
all of them

}

objects.name: wishfulwoodchuck_logfile_encodedheader
objects.description: YARA rule to detect related activity.
objects.pattern:
rule wishfulwoodchuck_logfile_encodedheader
{
    meta:
        author = "NCSC"
        description = "Encoded log file header"

    strings:
        $header = {41 19 0A 2D 20 59 5F FA 81 6F CF FF 61 9B D8 7B 2B 4B
46}
    condition:
        all of them
}
